<h2>2. Backtests are historical simulations</h2>

<p>
  The Services run parameter sweeps against TradingView's historical
  Strategy Tester. Results are <strong>historical simulations</strong>
  and are subject to all the well-known limitations of backtesting,
  including but not limited to:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Past performance is not indicative of future results.</strong>
    A strategy that performed well on historical data may lose money going
    forward.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Overfitting and curve-fitting.</strong> Optimizing parameters
    against a historical period can produce results that look excellent in
    the backtest but fail out-of-sample. The Services do not eliminate
    this risk; they can make it easier to produce overfit results.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Slippage, spread, and commission modeling.</strong> Backtest
    results depend on assumptions about execution costs that may not match
    what you experience with your own broker in live conditions.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Data quality.</strong> Results depend on the historical data
    made available by TradingView, which may contain gaps, adjustments, or
    inaccuracies that we do not control.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Market regime change.</strong> Market structure, liquidity,
    volatility, and correlations change over time. A strategy fitted to
    one regime may underperform or lose money in another.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Execution differences.</strong> Live trading involves order
    latency, partial fills, and venue differences that a backtest cannot
    fully reproduce.
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
  No representation is being made, and none should be inferred, that any
  strategy, parameter combination, or account will or is likely to
  achieve profits or losses similar to those shown in any backtest.
</p>

